text:
that grid, tho...â€panty portraitsâ€ from 
the panty project on exhibition now 
the wash (as it seams) 
january 21 - march 2
@msuunionartgallery @michigan_state_university_ .
the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text: jacqui orie (pictured) is a domestic worker and an organizer with the national domestic workers alliance. sheâ€™s doing important work, and raising awareness about the workplace abuses domestic workers are faced with in the united states. there are more than 2m domestic workers in our country, and only a handful of states guarantee them basic workplace protections. the domestic workers bill of rights passing would ensure that domestic workers are extended: the right to overtime pay when they put in more than 40 hours a week, the protections of the occupational safety and health administration, the ability to form unions, and ability to seek recourse against harassment and discrimination. it also extends new ones, such as the right to meal and rest breaks, paid sick days, advanced notice of scheduling, written agreements, and privacy and other protections for live-in workers. ğŸ’¥ğŸ™ŒğŸ½ these reforms are necessary. the omission of domestic worker rights is a legacy of slavery and race-related class discrimination.

text:
senior policy advisor for senator angus king wants to hear from mst survivors!!!! we had an interesting meeting yesterday with the office of senator angus king, (i-me). we spoke directly with his senior policy advisor, steve smith. a veteran himself, he seemed to have a deep concern for survivors of military sexual trauma. in fact, after trina mcdonald and myself shared our stories of rape in the military and the difficulties we both had in accessing va mental health care, mr. smith so graciously offered to hear directly from other mst survivors. he acknowledged that mst is not a gender issue rather an abuse of power. 
mr. smith highlighted the many provisions that have already been put in place to protect survivors and ensure that the process of reporting rape was one which is not only safer but also effective. he felt it would help the senator in his decision making about whether or not to vote in favor of the mjia by being better informed of the struggles service members and veterans face.  in fact, during our meeting mr. smith stated that he would personally like to hear directly from â€œnewer survivorsâ€. steve smith

the pain started in 2007 after a sexual assault. the guilt and shame alone was terrible, but on top of that i started to have a lot of pelvic pain. a visit to the gyno offered me the very vague diagnosis of pelvic inflammatory disease. i took all the antibiotics, but nothing was getting better, only worse. by 2010 i was having trouble walking. every step i took felt like a knife in my left ovary. later that year i was diagnosed with endometriosis via laparoscopy.
.
over the following years i experienced consistent pain with sex, gyno exams, and pelvic floor pt. more often than not, any of those activities might strike me in just the wrong way, resulting in shooting pain running from my vagina to my throat, vividly offering me memories and emotions that i couldnâ€™t quite place, and dissolving in a mess of tears i couldnâ€™t quite understand. it became clear to me then that emotional trauma was a significant contributor to my pain, and that it was somehow stuck â€œdown there.â€
.
fast forward through years of medical mismanagement. over time i took myself off hormonal birth control (yes, this is possible), i changed my diet, and began to slowly recognize my patterns of relating with myself and others, both sexually and non.ğŸŒ±
.
after becoming an acupuncturist i began seeing postpartum women who were in need of emotional recall and pelvic floor reconnection. it reminded me so deeply of my endo trauma. i felt called to do more, and i began to realize that this wasnâ€™t particular to any one diagnosis, but all women. it was therefore an easy choice when the calling came to teach somatic sexuality and embodiment in addition to managing healthcare. iâ€™ve since been in the ever-evolving process of creating and offering a multi-modality approach to allow women to gain the tools to communicate with their bodies and their sexuality, effectively overcoming shame and moving away from pain.ğŸ’¥
.
like all women, my life is littered with memories of having been touched in ways or being coerced  into doing things that made me uncomfortable at best, violated at worst. [cont. in comments ğŸ‘‡ğŸ¼]
name: Maggie Flood, L.Ac. CSB

text: when iâ€™m not doing calligraphy, i work full time as a social worker in special victims unit. i usually explain to people that iâ€™m like b.d. wong from law & order but admittedly less cool. my job is emotionally exhausting and rewarding at the same time, but there are moments that are bright. when i first saw this card made by @jess.mcsweeney for @littlewellpaperco, i bought it and hung it in my office so that victims could see it and feel heard. iâ€™m so grateful because jess ended up giving me two boxes of them. i met with a young girl recently and she expressed worry that her abuser would â€œget away with itâ€ and she wanted to â€œmake a protest like the me too movementâ€ if that happened. you should know that sexual abuse is a secretive crime and there is often a lack of physical evidence, relying mostly on testimonial evidence at trialâ€”making them difficult to prove #believeher. after doing this for so many years, i am pretty good at keeping my emotions in check but i almost let myself go here. what a strong girl. what a powerful movement that is going on right now. i told her that her young voice is important and she deserves to be heard. i canâ€™t wait to give her one of these cards to write down her feelings. the me too movement is about taking back a stolen power. bam. | photo by @stacy__yeager
name: Shotgunning for Love Letters

text:
with black history month coming to a close and womenâ€™s history month about to begin i thought tarana burke would be todayâ€™s ideal feature. 
tarana burke, a ny native and mom of one, became well known for her â€œ#metooâ€ movement in late 2017 when the allegations of film producer harvey weinsteinâ€™s sexual assaults were brought to the public light. 
although many of us were unfamiliar with tarana burke until recently, she has been putting the footwork into helping victims of sexual abuse for decades. her story begins in 1997 when a 13 year old girl confided to her that she had been sexually assaulted. not knowing what to say or even having the courage to say she  too had been sexually assaulted as a child, left tarana feeling very heavy.  she carried that weight for 10 years before deciding to start her organization, just be inc., which is a nonprofit that helps victims of sexual harassment and assault. 
since then, tarana has devoted herself to finding as many resources as possible to help people who are found in this very same situation.  she has built many celebrity relationships along the way and been able to bring awareness and speak on many platforms to promote her metoo movement.  through this movement alone so many have found their voice and been able to speak out on their abuse. tarana burke is changing lives and allowing the abused to learn to live, love and laugh again despite their abuse and weâ€™re here for it!

@taranajaneen we think you are fabulous and you deserve to be featured! ğŸ’•

text:
let's talk about consent... we've done a couple of episodes that dabble in the topic - we talked to a sex shop owner about kink, to a sex worker about their experiences in the industry, about the #metoo movement and our own experiences in it.
~
there still seems to be a lot of haze around the topic though. consent is permission. consent is not signing all the boxes, giving consent to one thing doesn't have a blanket effect.
~
consent is the most important part of any interaction with another human, especially in sex and it is particularly important in kink. why? because the platform in which kink is built is from trust. the reason those environments and communities are safe are because they are actively participating in conversation and consent.
~
it is a large playing field - and it is supposed to be play. so knowing what people are comfortable with, what is fun for them, but most importantly knowing that the people they are interacting with are listening to them. that if they say their safe word it will be heard. that they are still in control even if being dominated. taking away someone's consent is rape.
~
if you dont feel comfortable asking someone if they consent then you dont get to participate. and you should probably ask yourself why you don't want to confirm consent. a potentially fun situation can quickly turn scary and harmful if both parties aren't on the same page. there is a huge difference between abuse and play and it lays in consent.
~
have i said consent enough? i hope so. whether you want to stick your finger in someone's butt, have them call you a dirty whore, or tie them up... all have completely different connotations depending on whether or not... you got it... each party consents.

friends! are you familiar with white ribbon canada? their mission is to engage men and boys in the prevention of gender-based violence by promoting equity and transforming social norms. they challenge and support men and boys to realize their potential to be part of the solution in ending all forms of gender-based violence.

on may 29th they are doing their annual event in toronto - walk a mile in her shoes. it's a playful opportunity for men to raise awareness in their community about the serious causes, effects and remediations to men's sexualized violence against women. walk a mile in her shoes asks men to literally walk one mile in women's high-heeled shoes.

text:
hai sobat setara!
kami adalah komunitas diskusi yang mewadah di forum bernama square dari aplikasi messenger line yang diberi nama setara
.
.
di square line setara, kami mendiskusikan berbagai isu-isu sosial yang sedang santer, dan biasanya di hari jumat dan sabtu kami mengadakan forum rutin yang membahas isu tertentu dan berharap melalui diskusi-diskusi tersebut menghasilkan solusi efektif yang diharapkan dapat diterapkan dalam kehidupan setiap hari
.
.
.
di square setara, semua bebas menyampaikan aspirasinya asal masih dalam norma yang benar, bahkan mau random atau basa-basi atau curhat atau becanda pun juga boleh kok hehe. semua kalangan usia, gender, apapun itu punya kesempatan yang sama dalam menyuarakan pikirannya
.
.
yuk, buang ragu dan malu dan jadilah bagian dari keluarga setara dengan gabung di square line kami ya, sobat :)

text:
some days are harder than others. the pain in your chest is heavy, the fog in your mind is thick. leaving your bed to even brush your teeth or shower seems like climbing everest.

we all have these days, breathe, remember you are here. 
you are strong by just being and tomorrow is another day. 
take the time you need and you deserve today... and just breathe.

#abuse #rape #metoo #survivor #iamhere #iamstrong #loveyourself #mentalhealth #anxeity #cbt #ptsd #heal #love #loveyourself #youarehere

text: a public space books advance copies for reviewers/media of #bettehowland have arrived! it is a story that began with aps no. 23, which we now think of as the lost women issue, as it surfaced essential narratives by writers such as kathleen collins and bette howland for a new generation of readers. collins' collected stories were subsequently published by ecco, along with a nonfiction volume, notes from a black womanâ€™s diary, this year, which prompted @nytbooks to say, "the writer and filmmaker kathleen collins died in 1988, at the age of 46 â€” young, brilliant and, for the most part, unknown. it was a tragic if not entirely unusual fate. what was striking was how instantly her work was embraced after it was rediscovered â€” like a missing piece somehow anticipated and long yearned for." this highly-collectible issue, published in 2015 and available in our store at apublicspace.org, continues to reverberate into the world, with @andevers, founder of  @secondshelfbooks in london, noting in an interview with @bitchmedia this week, "i started working on the second shelf before #metoo and before trump was elected. the idea for the business came to me not long after iâ€™d visited a book fair in 2015 in new york and noticed the gender inequality in the room, and also from working at a freelance space in the office of a public space while they were putting out an issue on forgotten and overlooked women writers." our relationship with howland's work and her son, jacob, as we traced a line to her from the day that aps founding editor brigid hughes first encountered her book, w-3, @housingworksbks enriched and inspired our own experience in publishing to the extent that a public space books was born. calm sea and prosperous voyage will be published on may 7, and is distributed to bookstores by @publishersgroupwest (as is a public space magazine now!). for all media inquiries, contact @deweynicole @shrevewilliams #bookstagram

there is no better time than now for a production of ntozake shangeâ€™s famed choreopoem and award-winning stage play, â€œfor colored girls who have considered suicide/ when the rainbow is enufâ€, according to alicia johnson-williams, director.

commonly known as â€œfor colored girls,â€ the play will be staged at the encore theatre and gallery march 1-3. the performance is a series of 20 separate poems choreographed to music that weaves interconnected stories of love, empowerment, struggle and loss into a complex representation of sisterhood. the cast typically consists of seven, nameless african-american women who are only identified by the colors they are assigned.

johnson-williams talked about the timeliness of the canonical play, which originally opened in the 1970â€™s by shange, who died last year. â€œweâ€™re in the crust of the #metoo movement and #timesup but the fact is, time was always up,â€ said johnson-williams. â€œthis production speaks directly to women and how theyâ€™ve coped with these very issues that even today we still encounter and have to deal with as women and in particular as african american females in the united states of america.â€ johnson-williams said â€œfor colored girlsâ€ has always been an iconic production in african american theatre, particularly as it relates to women. the cast includes local artists such as teâ€™shara monique as the lady in purple; erika kellom as the lady in brown; juna givhan as lady in red; phaith â€œdj chocolateâ€ frazier as lady in blue; lashonda corder as lady in yellow #urbantheater #blacktheatre #blacktheater #blacktheatrematters #blactor #blactors #inspirationalquotes #motivation #graphicdesign #branding #design #theatre #theater  #birminghamalabama #urbantheatre #gospelplay #stagelife #actor #actorslife #talent @justladyshy @djchocolatedotcom @nadiatellismusic @wizdom_wita_z @sassieshanna @jgivhan

text:
now i have finished reading,  rebecca, i can breath again!
.
this was my real life book club read for february, and it is the first book we have all loved, hands down, without a doubt; it's been our favourite so far.
we had all read, rebecca, in our distant, misty pasts, and it was interesting comparing our thoughts and assumptions about the novel with our thoughts and feelings second time around, and having lived a lot more life.
one of these changes is how much more romantic we thought the novel in our younger days, and how much, much, darker it seems to us now. also, how much more nuance there is in the characters and their relationships, and in what is left unsaid. whereas we rooted for the new mr & mrs de winter all the way in the past, now we were not so sure. while we reviled mrs danvers as the villain of the piece in the past, we now held some sympathy for her. we were also left wondering what kind of love mrs danvers really held for rebecca, and what the narrator's jealousy was really directed at when she thought about rebecca; why she thought more about rebecca's presence than her husband's?
.
rebecca is such a great book for a book club read and discussion. we could have talked all night, but in a couple of hours we covered feminism, the english class system, gender and sexuality, manderley as a character, capital punishment, and the shocking end to the novel, which makes you realise you have to go back to the beginning to grasp the conclusion. brilliant!
.
thanks @remembery_tree_reads  for the #daffersanddaffodils .
.

text:
phantom lady is a more effective assemblage of noirish elements than my last reviewed film #sodarkthenight . however, any advance is stunted by a whole slew of logic problems and a plot that unfolds with all the dramatic suspense of an assembly guide for an ikea cupboard: you know the basic form itâ€™ll end-up taking, just not how itâ€™s going to get thereâ€¦

while the supporting players are all doing their best within the constraints of the material, only ella raines is, for me, making the most of whatâ€™s on offer. by contrast, both curtis & tone are both lumbered with one-note roles, devoid of opportunities for self-expression. forget the men: this is a movie geared towards a new audience of newly-empowered women, hungry to see their experience reflected in the movies.

ever keen to oblige, hollywood complied: just as itâ€™s doing today, though time will tell if the #metoo movement has longer, stronger roots than those encouraged by a world warâ€¦

text:
â€œyour fingers entwined with mine, and suddenly life made senseâ€.
.

the logical thing to do would have been for me to stand there tell the truth & say it's a guy i dated last year but because i felt panicked the words "i don't know who he is, he must be one of my brothers friends" fell out of my mouth quicker than the shit falls out your ass hole after a bad case of diarrhoea. i remember walking into my kitchen thinking "why the fuck have i just done that??" my higher self was floating above my head, tutting with disappointment. i felt sick and i was shaking and i realised that the reason why i lied was because i panicked. i felt like i had done something wrong...even tho i hadn't but that feeling triggered my old survival behaviour because of my experience with domestic violence.
.

text:
â€œyour fingers entwined with mine, and suddenly life made senseâ€.
.

the logical thing to do would have been for me to stand there tell the truth & say it's a guy i dated last year but because i felt panicked the words "i don't know who he is, he must be one of my brothers friends" fell out of my mouth quicker than the shit falls out your ass hole after a bad case of diarrhoea. i remember walking into my kitchen thinking "why the fuck have i just done that??" my higher self was floating above my head, tutting with disappointment. i felt sick and i was shaking and i realised that the reason why i lied was because i panicked. i felt like i had done something wrong...even tho i hadn't but that feeling triggered my old survival behaviour because of my experience with domestic violence.

text:
ensuring #metoo movement advances diversity in leadership
#
progress has been made in terms of womenâ€™s equality and protection over the past 10 years. in fact, it was recently the 10th anniversary of the lilly ledbetter fair pay act, the first bill signed into law byÂ presidentÂ barack obama in 2009. while there have been significant strides in reducing gender bias, harassment and sexual misconduct, clearly there is still work to be done. the #metoo movement has been an important driver in bringing to light numerous cases of sexual abuse and misconduct. however, it has also had the unintended consequence of causing men to refrain from interacting with women for fear of retaliation. considering that male executives play a key role in advancing women into higher levels of leadership, this fear must be taken seriously because if unaddressed it leads to workplaces where there are fewer opportunities for womenâ€™s career advancement and informal coaching. bloomberg recently conducted interviews with more than 30 senior executives that suggest many are startled by the #metoo movement â€” some for good cause while others succumb to fear and retreat from supporting leadership diversity. this is a huge problem for women, men, the companies they work for and society as a whole. when men shyâ€¦

text:
"it took me 30 years to realise this incident sent me on a path of being #overweight. i didnâ€™t want to be attractive to other men because of what this guy felt he could do to me. 
i was in my 20s and was a dental nurse in between permanent jobs, so i went to a temping agency and they told me there was a dentist in purley that needed some help. i went to the first session working with him and he seemed friendly enough and everything was fine. the second day when i went in, he started to be quite jokey and jovial and i didnâ€™t really think anything of it at first. as the morning progressed and we got into the afternoon, i started to realise that there was a thing happening, he was being very flirty and i tried to cool everything down. on the third day, he was really strongly flirting with me and he asked me if i had ever kissed a dentist. i told him i wasnâ€™t interested in kissing a dentist and that i had my own boyfriend at home. in between patients, he cornered me in the surgery and tried to force me to kiss him. i donâ€™t know how i managed it, but i got away and went straight to the toilet and locked myself in. i was really embarrassed; looking back i wonder why was i embarrassed, but i was. 
i decided that i couldnâ€™t stay and didnâ€™t want to go back into that surgery with that man; i felt really uncomfortable. i got my bag and told the receptionist i wasnâ€™t going to work with him anymore. she tried to make me stay as we had patients for the rest of the day, but i left. i then had to drive home and tell my boyfriend why i was home early. he was livid and wanted to go and see the dentist but i stopped him. i rang the agency up and told them not to place young women with him. 
now i am 50 and an old woman, i donâ€™t get this attention anyway and i am really motivated to lose the weight and get myself fit."
#nationaleatingdisordersawarenessweek

text:
"hey, come on! i thought you were mature enough to know the difference between maintaining personal and a professional relationship. i'm sure now you're comfortable enough with me to wear your backless white dress in a hotel room. trust me, you'll feel relaxed after our meeting." .

i was numb. i stood still. i had zero idea of what was going around me. i stood there feeling absolutely nothing. .

i still couldn't believe what i read. he had the audacity to say, "ofcourse we have met for work but this is personal." .

i sure did abuse him, replied him harshly, and made it crystal clear about never working with him. however, does that change the fact that someone appreciated your efforts only because they would like to sleep with you? .

how do you react to such a situation? please don't tell me to let it go and move on because this will keep on disturbing me time and again. if you feel like i asked for it or gave him hints, please unfollow me right away. .

when things like sexual harrassment repeat themselves, you still don't figure out how to react, what to do, or how to focus for certain period of time. you feel miserable and you end up doubting yourself. i ended up doubting my capabilities and talent. .

but then someone said, "this world might be a cruel place and you'll face many such assholes in your life. but never doubt on yourself. if you were not this talented, people wouldn't have appreciated your work. it isn't your fault. such people are cowards. this is just a stone in your way to success. kick it, don't stumble upon it. and once you do, emerge like the strong ass woman you are!" .

that must've not changed my life but it did help me. it did make me feel better. this coming from a male friend of mine made me believe that not all men are the same. .

you usually don't know what to say or do when someone shares such stories with you. having said that, the least you can do for them is to make sure you won't repeat the same mistake and stand up for something that's morally wrong. .

it feels good to open up and share this with you all. it feels good to know that i did not give anyone enough power to destroy me and my dreams.

text:
what happens when women speak up against harassment in scientific institutions? this week, we wrote a letter to chancellor zeppos @vanderbiltu showing our support for dr. bethann mclaughlin (@mclneuro on twitter) #metoostem founder, mit disobedience awardee, slayer of the rate my professor chili pepper, advocate for safety in science, teller of uncomfortable truths, and accountability bloodhound. dr. mclaughlin may lose her job on feb 28 - today- absent a last-minute reprieve from vanderbilt university. find out more in our #takeactiontuesday post. 
#womeninstem #womeninscience #metoo #womenlead #timesup

text:
the world is finally taking note of women taking the lead, becoming masters of their own destinies, building anchors and support systems among themselves and getting involved in championing development in their community. 
this is what african women in leadership organisation is all about. 
today i was on the early morning live interview at the national television station of the republic of cameroon crtv with awlo cameroon vice president mrs. yenwo bertha to talk about this and the coming official launching and inuaguration dinner of awlo cameroon this saturday.

i hope you too are taking note and taking sides ğŸ˜

join us on saturday for awlo cameroon official launch at franco hotel by 6pm prompt. @awloint 
our annual african women in leadership conference also comes up on 4th & 5th april in rwanda. register: awlo.org/awlc

text:
when was the last time god closed a door for you and you thanked him? when was the last time that you didnâ€™t get what you wanted; what you thought you needed? did you thank god then?
lately iâ€™ve been faced with a lot of closed doors. a lot of things havenâ€™t worked out as planned or as hoped. a lot of things havenâ€™t been in my favor. iâ€™d walk through one door, only for it to be shut in front of me. all the doors iâ€™ve been trying so eagerly to enter have been closed. iâ€™ve been stuck wondering, â€œwhat now?â€, â€œwhat comes nextâ€?itâ€™s natural to want to ask god why. to be frustrated and upset with him. to have a long list of questions and contemplations. but instead of asking him why, i think we should thank him. thank him for all those closed doors. all those decisions he made for you. thank him for those things that didnâ€™t work out. we donâ€™t always see it right then, but those closed doors means he has something better planned. that wasnâ€™t where you needed to be. those things, that person, that place, they werenâ€™t meant for you.the next time your plan doesnâ€™t work out or you donâ€™t get what you wanted, thank him. remember he closed that door with a purpose and a plan, much, much better.

text:
the world is finally taking note of women taking the lead, becoming masters of their own destinies, building anchors and support systems among themselves and getting involved in championing development in their community. 
this is what african women in leadership organisation is all about. 
today i was on the early morning live interview at the national television station of the republic of cameroon crtv with awlo cameroon vice president mrs. yenwo bertha to talk about this and the coming official launching and inuaguration dinner of awlo cameroon this saturday at franco hotel by 6pm.
i hope you too are taking note and taking sides ğŸ˜

text:
video taken inside a day care center in north #stlouis county shows a worker tossing a girl across the room and another injured child with some kind of â€œnail punctures on the skin,â€ a police sergeant said wednesday.

police began its investigation of brighter day care and preschool after a 3-year-old girl was taken by ambulance feb. 1 to a hospital with a deep gash on her head. she required seven stitches and later was hospitalized for three days after it became infected, her familyâ€™s attorney says.

video shows a worker grabbing the girl by the arm and tossing her across a room, said sgt. kevin smith with the north county police cooperative. as police officers were reviewing the video of that assault, they came across a second victim, smith said.

the second child had puncture wounds to the skin.

the child is â€œdoing pretty well now,â€ smith said. smith had no additional details on the child or that injury. smith said detectives would be seeking warrants soon.

smith said the workers involved in the two incidents were no longer working with the day care center. â€œwe can assure you the children are no longer in danger,â€ he said.

the director of the day care center declined to speak to a reporter wednesday, referring all questions to her attorney. he released a statement saying that â€œproviding a quality education in a safe environment is of the utmost importance to our teachers and staff.â€ the statement said the day care was cooperating with authorities.

the video of the worker tossing the 3-year-old girl was released to the post-dispatch by the familyâ€™s attorney, jennifer hansen.

hansen said the worker who grabbed the child filled out an â€œunintentional injury formâ€ and described the injury this way: â€œbump her head, when she fall out on carpet.â€ days after the injury, the girlâ€™s family pressed for more information from the day care centerâ€™s director to explain how falling on the carpet could produce such a serious injury, hansen said. the director told the girlâ€™s family that she had video of the room where the injury happened, but that she hadnâ€™t viewed it yet, hansen said.

to learn more visit legalactionnews.com

text:
it's been 4 years now.
this very day, four years ago, i remember. i was there. you were too. we already had a history. but we decided. to keep it aside. to not let it ruin what we had before. little had i known. you had something else on your mind. you weren't what i thought you were. obviously. you never could have. "there i was giving you a second chance. but you stabbed me in the back while shaking my hand." i remember you try to come to me. closer. and closer. i tried to stop you. i wished i was not alive to have experienced that. you touched. not where you were supposed to. i was shook. i trembled. i went blank into a void of much worse flashbacks. i came back to my senses. i couldn't have let it happen again. at least i now knew it was wrong. i pushed you again. with all the force that i had. and believe me, i could have shifted mountains with that rage i had. i kicked you out of my house. and my life. but i can never forget what it felt like. and how disgusted you made me feel since then. every year, today.
.
.
.
|| 8 ||
.
.
.
.

sometimes the answers to our 'whys' are right in front of us.

don't hide your scars.
don't hide your troubles.
don't hide your heartaches.
don't hide your disappointments.

allow those very things you feel make you less be the very things that lead you to more.

find those who cause you to say "me too", connect with them so they know they aren't alone in their hard and make the world a better place.

text:
you have no control over what has happened to you in the past. but you do have control over what happens in the present. 
own your pain. choose recovery. do not live with the pain that you can get rid of.

text:
consider this!!!!! self-love is one of the most important attributes for success and a key to breaking toxic cycles. it allows us to achieve more and live a healthy life with inner peace. the better you feel about yourself, the more you can accomplish. so, we want the best for our children, therefore, we must instill self-love into them as early as possible. not only does it help them accomplish their goals and dreams, but its a protection for them as well. *********
join me on march 20th at 7pm est (((link in bio))) for my next free webinar where we will discuss not only teaching self-love to our children, but the effects of the generation gap also. one more thing, i'll share my own story of childhood trauma and how i've overcome. everyone who attends will receive a copy of my 30 day breaking toxic cycles journal for free! sign up and share this link with others!!!!!
*********
i can't wait to grow, elevate, and assist you with breaking the cycles that have been holding you back!!!!!!!

text:
hello! my new #volg and #blog is out with many #reflective #conversations on the recent #diversity #fauxpas and then some #shoutouts too ğŸ”— link ğŸ‘† in bio shortly 
discussions on the recent #blackface
#controversy 
next, most noteworthy i believe is definitely gillette's, #thebestmencanbe #campaign and the backlash it received on account of calling out on #toxicmasculinity

next,  why is #sexualharassment #policy not #genderneutral

because of #metoo a lot of chatter is around framing sexual harassment #policies focused only on women. however, i have been relentlessly working on a more inclusive agenda i.e. framing policies for sure, but also ensuring they are gender-neutral.

biases oh biases! and ass boss!

i will also talk about #biases in the #workplace. how to deal with them. the need also stems from my own personal experiences as i have come across many hiring managers, leaders and decision-makers to have #narcissistic personalities and an inflated sense of self. heck, i haveÂ even worked with a few in the recent past! it's not just difficult to work with this type but also detrimental to one's mental health, well-being, and self-esteem. sometimes a tight slap (figuratively) and a walk-out is just sufficient! no matter what's the prevailing job climate, do not let such egomaniacs disintegrate your dignity.

oracle's sad scene

#oracle was recently accused of underpaying #women , #black and #asian employees. such disclosures are very likely trending in 2019. the classic invalidation of pinning #paygap to market forces isn't going to work now.

the #lens of #exclusion in the bias movie!

my own personal experience in dealing with errant companies. i have faced #exclusion challengesÂ not just as a #diversityrecruiter but also as a candidate. i've been in the starring role in the bias movie myself. believe me, it's frustrating to be perpetually "ignored" almost to a point of feeling invisible despite being the #protagonist :)

next, most noteworthy i believe is definitely gillette's, #thebestmencanbe #campaign and the backlash it received on account of calling out on #toxicmasculinity

next,  why is #sexualharassment #policy not #genderneutral

because of #metoo a lot of chatter is around framing sexual harassment #policies focused only on women. however, i have been relentlessly working on a more inclusive agenda i.e. framing policies for sure, but also ensuring they are gender-neutral.

biases oh biases! and ass boss!

i will also talk about #biases in the #workplace. how to deal with them. the need also stems from my own personal experiences as i have come across many hiring managers, leaders and decision-makers to have #narcissistic personalities and an inflated sense of self. heck, i haveÂ even worked with a few in the recent past! it's not just difficult to work with this type but also detrimental to one's mental health, well-being, and self-esteem. sometimes a tight slap (figuratively) and a walk-out is just sufficient! no matter what's the prevailing job climate, do not let such egomaniacs disintegrate your dignity.

oracle's sad scene

#oracle was recently accused of underpaying #women , #black and #asian employees. such disclosures are very likely trending in 2019. the classic invalidation of pinning #paygap to market forces isn't going to work now.

the #lens of #exclusion in the bias movie!

my own personal experience in dealing with errant companies. i have faced #exclusion challengesÂ not just as a #diversityrecruiter but also as a candidate. i've been in the starring role in the bias movie myself. believe me, it's frustrating to be perpetually "ignored" almost to a point of feeling invisible despite being the #protagonist :)

text:
sexism in social media discussion
wednesday 6th march, 3.15-4.15pm
muirhead, room 113
.
in recent months, the ability to call out sexism and misogyny on social media has transformed the feminist movement. twitter, facebook, instagram and various other forms of social media have provided a platform for feminists and others to raise awareness and address issues of prejudice against women. hashtags such as the #metoo movement and #everydaysexism are social media based feminist campaigns that aimed to gather examples of everyday experiences of sexism in one space. however, despite the opportunities social media has presented the feminist movement, digital platforms also leave women vulnerable to frequent sexist threats and attacks. how do we prevent online misogyny, and more importantly is social media a positive or negative space for women? 
this discussion is hosted by the edacs feminism group and will be led by final year english and history of art student rozeena.

rsvp on the @edacsbham facebook event or by emailing sophia robertshaw (s.f.robertshaw@bham.ac.uk).

text:
you've heard the story before
we see it time and again
women with the courage to speak
threatened by those who pretend

that she's making all this up
she's created some big lie
just to take him down
just to ruin his life

what i don't understand
when there's this pattern that we see
why would she want to speak
when she knows they won't believe

brett kavanaugh, donald trump, dr. luke
they all still walk free
why would it be any different
for the men who hurt you and me? 
multiple women come forward
told they are crazy, insane liars
with deceitful motives
lighting a match, starting a fire

they attack her character
paint her as vindictive
bitches who want to hurt them
when for years it's been unwritten

will there ever be a time
when they will see a consequence
or is she to forever hold her tongue
suppressed by his confidence

she'll keep standing tall
and speaking her truth
one day karma will find him
she'll feel nothing but a bruise

text:
usually i post about the astounding places i am experiencing in the different countries i am visiting; however, the people i am meeting and learning from around the world are equally as worthy of the attention. 
i had the pleasure of getting to hear from and speak to this amazing group of women today. mrs. anisha cherian is the founding member of raising our voices- an ngo in indiaâ€™s coastal kerala state that works to rehabilitate women and children who are victims of sexual violence, as well as raise awareness and education about the issue. sexual violence is a rampant problem in india. every 20 minutes, a woman is raped- and this only accounts for reported incidents. however, these courageous and brilliant women are working to spread the #metoo movement and prevent such atrocities from happening in their beloved nation. 
what strikes me most about these women is that they are just like you and i. when womenâ€™s issues started to get published in the media because of social media and the spread of the #metoo movement, these women banded together to have a discussion group about the issues. yet, they didnâ€™t stop there. while itâ€™s easy to talk about the issues occurring around us, it takes courage and strength to take action. in anishaâ€™s words, â€œwe can chose to be blind, or we can act.â€ so they did just that. now, their organization, raising our voices, works tirelessly to improve the issues of sexual violence and misconduct in kerala and break the social stigma around discussing these issues. 
these women are a great example of how discussion can lead to action, and action can lead to change. so, i challenge you to think twice about the discussions you are having today and how those discussions can spark positive change in the world around you. after all, change has to start somewhere. #sassp19

text:
a letter to the anxious minds:

there's the leaden limbs and the shaky hands. there's the waterfall of thoughts; the loud hum you've just gotten used to. there's the flinching and the loaded eyes. there's your heart trying to out run you. there's your mind telling you not to believe a word anyone says. there's the pull, like something has been pulled away from you and you need to be held forever to get back to your own body. there's the push, like the world is propelling you forward when all you want to do is curl up. there's the crippling insomnia, the inability to understand that thunder does not mean the sky is going to fall, the childlike mentality you fall into when nobody is there to say 'you're safe here'. there's the straight thoughts, the need for affection, the need for understanding, for curiosity, for oxygen. and then there's you, and if you aren't the bravest thing i don't know what is.

text: i saw this after leaving an appointment mon morning in the flatiron district. and believe itâ€˜s a sign! no matter how hard & impossible you think things are, i promise & i swear, that if you live an honest, transparent & purposeful life (unfortunately sometimes a most traumatic event delivers your purpose), there is most definitely a powerful force (god, or a beloved parent, or something indescribable) that is making sure, that you make all thatâ€™s good, happen on this planet. there is no question my amazing father, may he rip, teddy, is that force. not only have i saw signs in the past 9 months, but signs directly pointing to the fact that wants me to know itâ€˜s him. the 1st sign, the expiration date on my the order of protection against my abusive boyfriend, june 13, 2019. itâ€™s my parents wedding anniversary. on that date over 40 years ago, my mom & dad signed an agreement, a marital contract, that they will be together as a unit, by law, in life. & now up until this very same date, my ex partner & i consented to a legal agreement, that we would stay away from each other in every which way in life. after realizing this, i saw sign after sign that he wants me to be safe & that he wants me to make my life matter. iâ€™m a believer now. #thehalpernproject #creativityforapurpose #metoo #domesticviolence #domesticabuse #domesticviolenceawareness #domesticviolencesurvivor #enddomesticviolence #god #godisgood #pray #life #believe #grateful #purpose #photography #photo #photooftheday #picoftheday #instagram #igers #street #streetart #newyork #newyorkcity #nyc #advertising #ad #marketing #creative

text:
// #itoowasmolested by a father figure :: "sabke saath hota hai"//
.
.
"it longs back to a considerable amount of time. i was a young girl who was simply trying to sleep lying in a bed in presence of a man who was a father figure to me. i was quite dear to him but for the reasons that i am not comfortable with anymore. unaware of his intentions, i thought i am in a protected environment when he slid his hand into my shirt. i felt worse on realising what happened with me there! .
.
 on narrating this episode with my mother, i was exposed to a new side of it where she went through something similar at some point in her life. "sabke saath hota hai", she said. i never saw him again but he left me with a lesson, you are unsafe more here than an environment which you have never seen!" i am certain of being confident enough to stand tall against any similar act of my privacy violation! .
.
tag one friend and pledge to stand against the molestation in 'protected' environment. let us stand against it, together! .
.
from a session in collab with @wdc_mirandahouse. want us to do a session/workshop on your college campus? get in touch! .
.

text: the compilers of scripture knew the pain of exile. empire, corruption, enemy capture, prophecy, standing without and calling for justice are all well-worn themes in the bible. it's even been suggested that the story of the garden of eden depicts the "death" experienced by our ancient ancestors as being cast away from their home. what a powerful symbol for the experience of victims of abuse and assault! they are exposed -- all too young -- to the injustice of the world, the assumptions of order turned to chaos, and the evil inclination of humanity. as things stand, these victim-survivors are most often rejected by their communities and loved ones and experience the death of being banished from the garden. the good news of scripture is that god stands with those who are cast out. god's people explore how god is with them and how to worship god away from the garden, the temple, and the promised land.

text:
thinking back on the times when people have betrayed, used, manipulated, and abused you is never a pleasant thing...i told a friend that i would provide artwork to accompany an article that she is writing and here it is...and here are some of the thoughts that came to me while taking this photo.

#toxicmasculinity is real. the #metoo movement is real. if you are a person who is uncomfortable with these facts i would encourage you to push aside the defensive #emotions that may rise up within you, (the way that many #victims have had to push aside the memories of their very real experiences) and simply try listening. 
maybe this will help. 
there are tasty mushrooms that grow on this earth. there are also poisonous mushrooms that grow on this earth. the existence of poisonous mushrooms does not mean that all mushrooms will make you sick...many of them are wonderful, delicious, happily enjoyed...but the ones that aren't, those can kill you.  see, there is a fundamental difference between mushrooms and poisonous mushrooms, the same way that there is a fundamental difference between masculinity and toxic masculinity. both can, and absolutely do, #coexist. 
if you think that this is a fad, or phase, or just something that the liberal #media has cooked up...again i encourage you to simply stop, and just listen. listen to the #women (and men) in your lives, young and old, #conservative and #liberal, free-spirited or anxious, wealthy or struggling, tomboy or princess...there is absolutely no doubt in my mind that you will be surprised at how many of them, like me, have stories. pain, ridicule, shame, and pride mean most don't share them, but they still have them, just the same. #metoo

text:
people often see me as strong and there is certainly truth to it. however my nervous system is delicate. i do have a smaller â€window of toleranceâ€œ as they call it in trauma therapy that most people do. itâ€™s not something i like and so i often forget about it, overestimate myself and take on situations with a lot of intensity for my nervous system. what happens then is i am overwhelmed, need boundaries and space for myself to regulate my nervous system and if there is not enough space i retreat into my core until intensity has past. needing alot of time after to myself. but if in that time afterwards another trigger happens my nervous system does whatever it does to regulate. itâ€™s bit scary to loose control over my body. my circulation often gets very low and then i get into hardly controllable shaking - the bodyâ€˜s reaction to get warm and release frozen life force. actually you can see that as a normal reaction in animals after trauma. they do not move at first and then often shake and then move about normal business. 
well, i hardly have had these episodes of ptsd as i live my normal life tuned to my capabilities. often it may underwhelm people if they get to live close with me. however this last episode really made me understand and accept myself more and pour love into that wounded part.  i often overlook it or not feel i want to give much attention to so i am not victimizing myself. but itâ€™s not how it heals and what love wants. i like to learn to accept this part with love yet not be defined or limited by it. that means: i have to stand up more firmly when i need boundaries and at times stretch them gently too. but that has to be initiated from me and not the outside. mmm quite the learning. 
who else is living with ptsd / trauma and what how do you manage intense situations. intense for you is often not even considered intense for someone else. 
love to hear from others. dm me. 
__________________________________________________

people often see me as strong and there is certainly truth to it. however my nervous system is delicate. i do have a smaller â€window of toleranceâ€œ as they call it in trauma therapy that most people do. itâ€™s not something i like and so i often forget about it, overestimate myself and take on situations with a lot of intensity for my nervous system. what happens then is i am overwhelmed, need boundaries and space for myself to regulate my nervous system and if there is not enough space i retreat into my core until intensity has past. needing alot of time after to myself. but if in that time afterwards another trigger happens my nervous system does whatever it does to regulate. itâ€™s bit scary to loose control over my body. my circulation often gets very low and then i get into hardly controllable shaking - the bodyâ€˜s reaction to get warm and release frozen life force. actually you can see that as a normal reaction in animals after trauma. they do not move at first and then often shake and then move about normal business. 
well, i hardly have had these episodes of ptsd as i live my normal life tuned to my capabilities. often it may underwhelm people if they get to live close with me. however this last episode really made me understand and accept myself more and pour love into that wounded part.  i often overlook it or not feel i want to give much attention to so i am not victimizing myself. but itâ€™s not how it heals and what love wants. i like to learn to accept this part with love yet not be defined or limited by it. that means: i have to stand up more firmly when i need boundaries and at times stretch them gently too. but that has to be initiated from me and not the outside. mmm quite the learning. 
who else is living with ptsd / trauma and what how do you manage intense situations. intense for you is often not even considered intense for someone else. 
love to hear from others. dm me.

text: #metoo. i am done being ashamed for something that someone else should be ashamed of. on june 2, 2016, i went to my first party and i was raped by eran sherman. in december of 2017, i opened up about it, realizing the damage it had done to me. in december of 2018, i went to the police to report the incident and made my own damage worse, trusting the justice system to patch me back up. yesterday, the justice system failed me and decided not to press charges and prosecute my case. i didn't report for me, i did it for everyone else so no one would have to feel what i've had to feel. i say me too so that somebody else in the future won't have to. and if the government won't let me do that on their platform then i will do it on my own. eran sherman is a rapist. i am not doing this for attention or pity. i am doing this for the girls that might be harmed by him in the future, or who already have been. i hope that someday the perpetrator will be the one bearing the consequences of their actions, not the victim. #metoo.

while speaking to variety, dennis graham a.k.a drakeâ€™s dad gave his thoughts on r-kelly and jussie smollett..his thoughts on r-kelly: â€œheâ€™s a good friend of mine. i wish him the best. i hate that itâ€™s happening to him. thereâ€™s a reason why women come out after the fact. he has my support 100%,â€ just as graham contemplates the reasoning behind why victims of sexual abuse come forward, we contemplate why dennis graham, is a thing at all? 
but donâ€™t color us surprised that his thoughts lean this way, this is a person who has insinuated that women endure abuse by putting themselves in certain situations saying: â€œbut there is something i want to say to these young ladies that allow themselves to go and be in a manâ€™s room or whatever. stop going to these hotels.â€ & â€œtake your ass home. don't go into a man's room.â€ (tmz) he further stated (in the past): whenÂ tmzÂ presses, asking if there are two sides to blame, he vehemently says no. â€œno thereâ€™s not two sides to blame. you take your ass home,â€ he said. â€œdonâ€™t go where you might think a man is going to have anything to do with raping you or anything else.â€ umm why are publications like variety interviewing someone like this over his (not newsworthy) single?? because heâ€™s drakeâ€™s dad? when you know better do better, we canâ€™t allow mouthpiecesâ€™ like these get ahold of a micâ€¦we donâ€™t know if heâ€™s committed abuse in the past himself but heâ€™s certainly an abuser sympathizer

text:
"a deeper sense of being" series 31 of 44.

become a patron and get exclusive access to poetry videos for just $5/month!

www.patreon.com/unjuliwrites

a deeper sense of being

her mouth speaks rainbows
and her lips
have the faint trace
of humility and grace. 
her hair is
waves of austerity
rooted in
the consciousness 
of her intricate mind. 
delve deeply 
into her soul
and you will find
a brave lion
triumphantly basking
in the aftermath
of a chase
that she has 
won fairly. 
she is there. 
right there
where she belongs. 
freedom is
her middle name
and this is her version 
of the game
of life. 
ask her twice
why she still
delicately 
plants seeds 
into buckets of forgiveness 
and she will tell you
that there is
an abundance of hope
which never dies. 
fortune lays around
her bare feet
and her toes
greet each new step
with a healthy dose
of mindful compassion. 
there is less stress
then there ever has been,
since the birth
of her new way of living
conquered 
the pent-up energy
which was keeping her down. 
you might be astounded
to discover
that her heart doesn't beat;
it pounds ferociously 
because her will
is so strong
it can shatter 
any unwelcome thought
with the sleight
of a finger. 
imagine what she can do
with her hands. 
look into her
candlelit eyes
and you will see
a version of yourself
you never thought
you'd see:
a tree so dense 
that rain 
never reaches the ground
with roots tucked 
under folds of 
cement barriers
reaching all the way
to middle-earth.

point to her
curvy lines 
and you will find
a sequence
of verses
which soothes minds
with the ease
of a simple
raindrop. 
she is a forest
with fires and rivers

text:
so honored to be a part of this film, and to help carry out the vision of gabi faye levin...to draw attention to the #metoo movement & to take survivors of sexual assault seriously.
this film initially started out with the name #metoo, but was influenced by my dirty girl gardening bus, which was a prominent feature in the film...the name organically changing into dirty girl as the process went on.
i play the bus driver, and also featured are one of my current employees & a past employee as survivors of assault, along with many other women (some professional actors) that i had not met before filming.

last night, a short clip of the film's trailer played on multiple screens in times square, nyc!! #dirtygirlgardening #dirtygirlthefilm #metoo #dirtygirl #womeninfilm #gabifayeproductions #timessquare #movietrailer #womenfilmmakers #dirtygirlbus #sexualassault #speakout #survivors #believesurvivors #timesup #yadone #gabifaye #womenmakemovies #believewomen #womensreality #iamanastywoman #empowerwomen
@gabifaye
name: Dirty Girl Gardening

text:
there are several theories as to how yamaguchi maho came about to be ambushed and assaulted at her dormitory.

firstly, in a now deleted tweet, yamaguchi maho mentioned that her address and private information had been leaked by some members.

secondly, according to a ngt48 management statement, an unnamed member provided information on maho.

thirdly, according to shuukan bunshun (a japanese weekly magazine), the assaulters have been living across mahoâ€™s unit for a year and a half.

now, 2ch netizens are speculating that the first leak of ngt48 membersâ€™ dormitory address may have started from temporary staff at ngt48 theater to inaoka. inaoka is a well-known ngt48 wota (someone who is a fan of idols or idol groups) as well as speculated to be an idol hunter.

an idol hunter is someone who uses any method that would allow them to enter the innermost sphere of the idol, and causes discomfort or damage to related persons. (see definition of idol hunter:
http://qqpy.tumblr.com/post/182174943121/what-makes-an-idol-hunter-a-blog-about-distance)

from inaokaâ€™s deleted tweets, internet sleuths found that he claimed to have sold personal information of idols to tabloids, boasted about stalking idols to their residences, and thatÂ he has had s*x with idols.

text:
a open form on masculinity for the modern man

hit link in bio for details march 2th sold out

sponsored by remi martin @woodylovell 
the barbershop club is a barbershop that is recognize to be the safe haven for manhood. masculinity is ingrained in the philosophy, while male grooming stands side-by-side with the commandments of being a gentleman , you can rest a sure that with over thousands of conversations had with man from all walks of life we are here to make the world a better place one haircut at a time. join us for and open form aimed at men and their unique challenges and interests. we explore all things manly â€” from the serious and philosophical to the practical and fun. we seek to uncover how to live with grandpaâ€™s swagger, virtue, and know-how in the present age by wedding the best of the past to the best of the present. showcasing experts on the art of masculinity.  the end goal is to create a synergy of tradition and modernity that offers men a way forward and signposts on how to live an excellent, flourishing life.
ultimately, the the barbershop club aims to encourage our men to be better husbands, fathers, brothers, citizens â€” a new generation of great men.

dedicated to uncovering the lost art of being a man.

regrooming masculinity unleashes the power of the barbershop to re-imagine menâ€™s gender identities and foster their diversity. by challenging stereotypes about men and masculinity, we investigate how men construct their identities through appearance and how the barbershop can be a vital tool to advance social change. this feminist-driven project creates a new approach to understand and transform how men see themselves, interact with each other, and engage with women.

text:
whilst i was recovering and trying to put my life back together piece by piece, i was told by a lot of people (professionals included) i needed to forgive the person(s) who had put me through the pain.

i understand this is a big part of the healing process for many but for me, personally, i have and wonâ€™t ever forgive. i use and channel my anger instead for good purposes. 
i am involved and help run a charity which teaches children what legal consent is. i have used the pain and anger to run a half marathon and get fit. most importantly i use my experiences to heal and better myself and i will qualify as a solicitor and master of law later this year. 
i want to do a lot more to help others as i get stronger with the qualifications i have achieved. 
remember it is your healing journey and you need to do whatâ€™s right for you. donâ€™t let anyone tell you what you should or should not be feeling, follow your own path and be your own guide ğŸ˜˜

self-care isn't #bubblebaths and #facemasks, though those are examples of techniques you can use. #selfcare is an attitude shift, a conversation shift in your head. 
the old you would wake up with lists in your head of all the things you need to accomplish. 
the new you is practicing waking up with lists of all the ways you are going to support yourself throughout the day. 
the new you stops to ask: what do i need? 
what do i want? 
several times a day, as you work towards a mindset shift that brings balance between what you do for others and what you do for yourself. 
that's #selfcare and it doesn't cost you anything. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €

we all want & need to be loved.
everyone's heard of #metoo. but no one has discussed the issues involved.
â€¢
because, primarily men, abused primarily girls and young women, those women then thought that guys want sex. so that's what they did/ do with every man.
â˜†
can you see the problem?
â€¢
guys brain's are wired different to women. guys want love too. but they see sex & love as separate. whereas women see it as the same thing. â€¢
those women have got *stuck* in a cycle, wanting love, but not knowing how to get it (& by thinking that they need to give sex in order to get love...which, simply, just isn't true).
â€¢
we get & receive love by forming healthy relationships over a period of time. building relationships. caring about each other. it's based on friendship. give & take. social skills. it takes time to build a loving relationship (years, not weeks/ months). both parties must be on the same page& want the same things in life (which should be established at the start).
â˜†
it affects billions of people all over the world. it affects men's ability to have loving relationships, as much as women's. it's our whole society.
â˜†

text: this is tarana burke! back in 1997 she sat across from a 13-year-old girl and listened to her experience of sexual abuse. the story left ms. burke speechless. she realized that she didnâ€™t know what to say or how to help her. ten years later she created the organization just be incorporated which is an organization that works to help victims of sexual harassment and assault. the name of the movement this inspired? me too. despite the credit given alyssa milano for popularizing #metoo it was actually originally coined by tarana burke. it was pointed out by many black women that tarana had been working tirelessly to help victims but she had been largely ignored by white feminists. shocker. april reign, the woman who started #oscarssowhite said â€œwhite women have not been as supportive as they could have been of women of color when they experience targeted abuse and harassment,â€ using the espn anchor jemele hill and actress leslie jones as examples. she explained that this was the time for everyone to realize that the only way feminism will work is if it is intersectional. tarana was afraid her life work was about to be co-opted but the quick response by social media made sure that didnâ€™t happen. we cannot imagine going back to a world before #metoo changed everything. and because of tarana burke we donâ€™t have to. thank you, tarana.

my beautiful flower
you donâ€™t even know how strong you are
how deep your roots
how full of love your soul and heart

text:
365 .
part 3 .

in october i filmed for wow women of wrestling television series .

later in the month i returned to vegas to work with my teams there and visit mom again. .

end of october our team goes into nation qualification doing over 160,000 in sales that month. .

november i head to palm desert for our area manager retreat. .

jacob returns home for thanksgiving, our team finishes our month with over 191,000 in sales. .

december i get down to my fighting weight of 110 lbs .

jacob returns home for christmas .

end of december our team finishes nation qualification along side my arbonne twin esmie with time to spare.  we dub ourselves the glow nation. .

in january our teams starts coaching over 147 detoxers on our 30 days to healthy living program. .

jacob and i are flown to maui compliments of arbonne and i attend my first ever nvp leadership retreat .

later in jan iâ€™m back in vegas to work with our teams there and visit my mom again. .

in february kinga and i fly back in poland to celebrate martaâ€™s region promotion and to give her the keys to her brand new white mercedes. .

you can call me an overachiever but iâ€™d rather you call me an overcomer. .

i believe that sometimes you have to get knocked down lower than you've ever been, to stand up taller than you than you ever were. .

iâ€™m not done honoring mike, i know i canâ€™t bring him back but what i wanted to do more than anything was to make him proud. .

he always worried about everyone he loved and i know that seeing the impact his death made had to be just as hard on him as it was for all of us. .

i wanted this year to become something we could all grow from instead of something that destroyed us. .

i hope you felt the same way.

maybe i am a feminist and a person who thrives in female company, solidarity and partnership because of something that happened in my family, or something that was ingrained in me at a young age. maybe i blame society too much and i judge men too harshly. thatâ€™s what (disclaimer: i am for normalizing therapy and i also think everyone should do it at least for a while) my therapist suggested today. or maybe, i am a woman and i know for a fact i am privileged because i have only experienced harassment and micro aggressions from men, while i listen to other womenâ€™s stories. but you know what? i donâ€™t really care about why. i am a feminist and i will always be one. feminism affects me personally, but i will always stand for the oppressed and learn how to be a better ally for the unprivileged. i donâ€™t care why. (i apologize for using gendered language, and i also would like to point out that while i have that uterus print in my wall my feminism is 100% inclusionary)
.
.

text:
survivors of sexual violence are often asked why they didnâ€™t try fight back. when we are faced with danger our bodies automatically respond-we go into survival mode. for example our hearts might begin to beat faster, we may breathe faster and harder and our muscles may tense up. 
common reactions to sexual violence are to â€˜freezeâ€™, â€™flopâ€™ or â€˜befriendâ€™, sexual violence is about power and control. perpetrators are often â€˜trustedâ€™ people in our lives, stronger than us or have a form of control over us. survivors explain that they felt frozen with fear or unable to control their bodies,  others try to be kind, friendly and polite to potential attackers thinking this may stop them from assaulting them. 
please watch this video for more information on what not to say to a survivor of sexual assault: â€˜things not to say to someone who's been sexually assaultedâ€™ made by bbc on youtube.

text:
music is not the only medium through which womxnâ€™s voices will be featured on march 8th! art share l.a. is proud to present female gaze, an opening art reception happening alongside femme frequencies showcasing the work of 19 los angeles based artists. join us on friday, march 8, 2019 for an opening reception in the main gallery from 7 - 10pm.
.
featuring work from:
sarah gail armstrong, lara solanki brennan, claudia cogo, kitty davies, eliza day-green, luka fisher, june harley, caroline heer, marina heintze, alexis hunley, maura latty, kyra leah, babsi loisch, paloma montoya, amanda sade, tslil tsemet, roni weiss, anna wong-nelson, moy young
.
what is the female gaze? the male gaze is a term coined by feminist film theorist laura mulvey, representing the viewpoint of the male viewer, character, or creator in placing women to be objectified and viewed as spectacles â€” unable to dismiss or return the same gaze towards those male counterparts. mulveyâ€™s term can be applied to any artistic form, from film and music to fine art and performance art.
.
under our current administration, and in the #metoo and timeâ€™s up era, what does this mean for how art is made and exhibited, by whom and for what audience? do we recognize this male gaze, reject it, change it, dissolve it? does it even still exist as a binary gender-based perspective, or has it evolved to signify any imbalance of power and agency? who defines the term, the viewer, or the viewed?
.
art share l.a.â€™s female gaze presents our experience as females, femme-identifying, non-binary, and ally communities in 2019 by staging a public forum for an on ongoing dialogue. what does the world look like through our gaze? and how that inevitably influences our creative practice.
.
